======================================================================
PART 2: IS 1, 1, 2, 3, 7, 19 A KNOWN SEQUENCE?
======================================================================

  Ratios:
    a(2)/a(1) = 1/1 = 1.0000
    a(3)/a(2) = 2/1 = 2.0000
    a(4)/a(3) = 3/2 = 1.5000
    a(5)/a(4) = 7/3 = 2.3333
    a(6)/a(5) = 19/7 = 2.7143
  First differences: [0, 1, 1, 4, 12]
  Second differences: [1, 0, 3, 8]

  Testing linear recurrences:
    a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-2)?  a(5) = 3+2 = 5 ≠ 7
    a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + a(n-2)?  a(5) = 6+2 = 8 ≠ 7
    a(n) = 3*a(n-1) - a(n-2)?  a(5) = 9-2 = 7 ✓
    a(n) = 3*a(n-1) - a(n-2)?  a(6) = 21-3 = 18 ≠ 19
    a(n) = 3*a(n-1) - a(n-2) + a(n-3) - a(n-4)?
    a(6) = 3*7 - 3 + 2 - 1 = 19 ✓ (but overfitted to 6 terms)

  Known sequences for comparison:
  Fibonacci:   1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, 21
  Lucas:       1, 3, 4, 7, 11, 18
  Motzkin:     1, 1, 2, 4, 9, 21, 51
  Catalan:     1, 1, 2, 5, 14, 42
  Bell:        1, 1, 2, 5, 15, 52
  Pell:        1, 1, 2, 5, 12, 29
  Schroeder:   1, 1, 2, 6, 22, 90
  Our seq:     1, 1, 2, 3, 7, 19
  Closest match: starts like Fibonacci (1,1,2,3) but diverges at a(5)

  Ratios approach: 7/3 = 2.3333, 19/7 = 2.7143
  e = 2.7183...
  If next ratio ~ e, a(7) ~ 19*e ~ 52

