PART 5: FOURIER ENERGY RATIOS — CLEAN FORMULAS
======================================================================

  Level-4 data:
    n=5: N_4 = 60, c_4 = 1/8, E_4 = 60/64 = 15/16
    n=6: N_4 = 720, c_4 = 1/8, E_4 = 720/64 = 45/4

    n=5: E_4/E_0 = (15/16)/(225/4) = 1/60
    n=6: E_4/E_0 = (45/4)/(2025/4) = 1/45

  N_4 values: 60, 720
  60 = 5!/2 = 60
  720 = 6! = 720
  Ratio: 720/60 = 12 = 6*2 = C(6,2)/... hmm

  4-arc subsets of K_5 covering all 5 vertices: 135
  But N_4 = 60, so 60/135 = 0.4444 = 4/9 are nonzero
  The 'adjacent' condition for level-4 selects 4/9 of them

  *** EUREKA: N_4(5) = 60 = number of Hamiltonian paths in K_5! ***
  An undirected Hamiltonian path of K_5 uses exactly 4 edges.
  And K_5 has 5!/2 = 60 undirected Hamiltonian paths.
  So the level-4 Fourier coefficients correspond to
  HAMILTONIAN PATHS of the complete graph!

  For n=6: N_4 = 720 = 6! = directed Hamiltonian paths in K_6
  For n=5: N_4 = 60 = 5!/2 = undirected Hamiltonian paths in K_5
  Inconsistency! Let me recheck.
  5! = 120 (directed), 5!/2 = 60 (undirected)
  6! = 720 (directed), 6!/2 = 360 (undirected)

  Verified from data: level-4 subsets ARE Hamiltonian paths of K_5!
  N_4(5) = 60 = # undirected Hamiltonian paths of K_5

  At n=6: N_4 = 720 (if all |c_4| = 1/8)
  C(15,4) = 1365 total 4-subsets
  720/1365 = 0.5275
  720 = 6! = directed Hamiltonian paths of K_6? Or something else?

  4-edge spanning subgraphs of K_6 (undirected):
    Type (3,1): path_3 + edge = 15 * 12 = 180
    Type (2,2): two disjoint paths of length 2 = 10 * 9 = 90
    Total spanning: 270
    N_4(6) = 720 ≠ 270, so level-4 subsets may NOT all span K_6

  NOTE: Need to verify if level-4 coefficients at n=6 are all 1/8
  This was only confirmed for n=5 in the data.

